Climate Change Topics on Twitter

Emily Huang, Kathy Huo, Nawat Swatthong, Kuang-Yu Wang, Vivian Wong



Climate change is a global-scale issue. As we need as many people as possible in the world to be aware of this issue and change their habits to protect the environment, how they view this issue is significant. People’s opinions upon this issue vary depending on their cultural background, socioeconomic status, education levels, and so on. To gather those different perspectives from people around the world, Twitter as a popular social media with users all over the world, serves as the best dataset.

For this project, we have identified several relevant studies and data sources related to climate change and public opinion on Twitter. The climate change Twitter dataset presents a comprehensive dataset regarding climate change and human opinions via Twitter, and provides insights into how people discuss climate change on Twitter and the various topics that are important to them. Exploring climate change on Twitter using seven aspects: Stance, sentiment, aggressiveness, temperature, gender, topics, and disasters also provides a comprehensive view of the different topics and aspects of climate change that are discussed on Twitter. Finally, NASA’s climate change website provides data on various climate indicators, which helps us understand the changes in climate over time and the potential impacts.

Global Warming Indicator Trends

The severity of global warming has led to significant environmental changes over the past two decades, as evidenced by various vital signs such as carbon dioxide concentration, sea level, ice extents, and Antarctic mass. The concentration of carbon dioxide has increased by over 11% during the past two decades, which is positively correlated with the global mean sea level, which has increased by 59.04 mm in total. Furthermore, the decrease in both Antarctic mass and global ice extents, as demonstrated in the bottom plot, has been observed, with the Antarctic mass declining sharply from -7 Gt in 2002 to -2638 Gt in 2021, and the ice extents exhibiting a decreasing trend with a negative slope despite some fluctuations.

Overall, the data presented in this visualization highlights the alarming environmental changes occurring due to global warming, including rising carbon dioxide concentrations, sea levels, and declining Antarctic mass and global ice extent.



Human influences are the number one cause of global warming, especially the carbon pollution we cause by burning fossil fuels and the pollution capture we prevent by destroying forests. The carbon dioxide, methane, soot, and other pollutants we release into the atmosphere act like a blanket, trapping the sun’s heat and causing the planet to warm (Denchak, 2022).

The Earth’s temperature has increased at a very rapid rate. The world’s maximum average temperature rate at 1850 was 35.645 degrees Celsius. This value has increased over the decades, and by the year 2010, the maximum average temperature of countries in the world reached 37.75 degrees Celsius.

This rise in temperature can be seen across countries in the world. It is known that the middle east region is heating up twice as fast as the globe. In the year 1950, the United Arab Emirates had an average temperature of 35.066 degrees Celsius. By the year 2010, the number had increased to 37.75 degrees Celsius.



How People and Tweets React To Climate Change

The visualization displays a clear correlation between temperature and latitude, with higher latitudes having lower temperatures. Arizona is the hottest southern state, in keeping with this correlation. Despite Twitter users tending to express negative sentiments more often than positive ones, Idaho has the highest average sentiment score from 2007-2019. Most states’ sentiment scores remain below zero, indicating a negative tendency overall.

Taking a closer look at the data, a trend emerges among Arkansas, Kansas, Wyoming, and Idaho. From 2007-2010, these states had high average sentiment scores of around 0.1, but the trend disappeared from 2016-2019. Instead, Idaho’s aggressiveness score increased significantly to around 0.5, while the scores for the other three states remained around 0.3. This suggests that factors beyond temperature may influence sentiment and aggressiveness over time, challenging the previously assumed clear relationship.



When we explored the changing pattern of both the average temperature and the average score of sentiment over a number of years, we found a similar changing pattern between them, particularly beginning in the year 2011. (The dataset that we are using has far less records during the first few years; as a result, we are making the assumptions in this section that the disparity between the shifting patterns at the beginning could have been caused by the lack of data records.) As a result, there is considerable evidence indicating that people’s sentiments are correlated with the temperature.

Note: this section here can only demonstrate that temperature and people’s sentiment are related to each other, but we cannot draw the cause and effect conclusion from this graph and conclude that the change of temperature can cause the change of sentiment.



Up until 2014, the Weather Extremes subject was the most trending topic on Twitter, although its popularity has since been overshadowed by other political problems. The subject of Global Stance replaced it, and Weather Extremes rose to around the fourth-most popular twitter topic.

However, other environmental-related subjects like Seriousness of Gas Emissions and Significance of Pollution Awareness Events have not received as much attention.



Natural Disasters and Tweet Sentiment

As the impacts of climate change become increasingly severe, natural disasters are also more common. Analyzing the sentiment of tweets related to natural disasters may reveal how people perceive and respond to such events. We created an interactive visualization, that features a world map that displays the average sentiment scores of tweets and a bar chart of different types of disasters of each countries.

The world map is encoded with colors that represent the average sentiment scores of tweets, ranging from -1 to 1 on a continuous scale. The sentiment scores are depicted using shades of orange for negative sentiment and shades of blue for positive sentiment. Additionally, values close to 0 and colors close to white are represented as neutral or having no sentiment. This allows for a quick and easy visual comparison of sentiment across different countries, with darker shades indicating more extreme sentiment.

Below the world map, a bar chart presents the different types of disasters documented in the dataset. When clicking on countries in map, the bar below reveals the types of disasters documented in each country, providing an interaction and more details. It is important to note that the dataset may not capture all the disasters worldwide, and thus, the results may not be entirely comprehensive. This stull visualization serves as a valuable tool for comparing sentiment associated with different types of disasters in various countries and obtaining insights into the average sentiment of each country.

Conclusion

The evidence presented in the visualizations clearly illustrates the severity of global warming and its impacts on various environmental indicators. The increase in carbon dioxide concentration, rising sea levels, declining Antarctic mass, and shrinking global ice extents are all alarming trends that highlight the urgent need to address climate change. The changing pattern of sentiment on as Twitter, in response to climate change and natural disasters further emphasizes the growing concern and awareness among the public.

The visualizations also highlight the complexity and multi-faceted nature of the issue, with factors beyond temperature, such as geographic location and other socio-political influences, potentially impacting people’s sentiment and response to climate change.

Climate change is a pressing global issue that requires urgent action at all levels, from individual behaviors to policy and systemic changes.With these visualizations, we can better understand the complex dynamics of climate change and make informed decisions to mitigate its effects and work towards a more sustainable future.
